<dl id="n40039d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40039d">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40039d"> 39(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> poor devil</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">From the various characteristics associated with this idea, the term <font color="green">[devil]</font> has come to be applied by analogy in many different senses. From the idea of evil as degraded, contemptible and doomed to failure, the term is applied to persons in evil plight, or of slight consideration. <small> &ldquo;DEVIL&rdquo; <a name="EBDV" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBDV"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) VIII 121</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
